message.content:
The effects of caffeine on the human body typically begin within around 15-45 minutes after consumption and can last for several hours. Caffeine is a natural stimulant that affects your central nervous system, including your brain, spinal cord, and other nerves.

Here are some common ways in which caffeine affects different parts of the body:

1. Brain: Caffeine blocks adenosine receptors in the brain, which leads to increased alertness and reduced feelings of fatigue. It also causes increased focus and possibly improved cognitive function; however, excessive amounts may contribute to anxiety or irritability.

2. Heart: As a stimulant, caffeine can increase heart rate temporarily. This effect might be more pronounced if you're not used to consuming it or if you consume large quantities at once.

3. Metabolism: Caffeine has been shown to increase basal metabolic rate (BMR) by about 3-11%, meaning your body burns more calories while at rest when you've consumed this substance.

4. Breathing: If someone suffers from asthma symptoms or other respiratory issues, an adequate dose of caffeine may provide minor relief because it helps widen airways briefly – but should never replace prescribed medication.

5-6%. Fat Usage & Weight Control: Moderate intake leads towards higher fat oxidation rates because catecholamine production increases significantly when coffee is ingested – hence why people often believe caffeinated beverages aid weight loss efforts due their appetite-suppressing properties too!
